Promises in JavaScript are like a container for a value that may not be available right away. They help to manage asynchronous operations by providing a way to handle the eventual resolution or rejection of an operation, and allow you to chain multiple operations together.

Here's a simple explanation:

When you make an API call, send an email, read from a file or do any other asynchronous operation, you don't always get the result immediately. Instead, you might get a Promise object that represents the operation's eventual result.

A Promise has three possible states: pending (not yet resolved), fulfilled (the result is available) or rejected (an error occurred). When you create a Promise, it's initially in the "pending" state. You can then add callback functions to the Promise using `.then()` and `.catch()` methods, which will execute when the Promise is either fulfilled or rejected, respectively.

