fn is_even(n: i32) -> bool {
    match n {
        0 => true,
        1 | 3 | 5 | 7 => false,
        2 | 4 | 6 | _ => is_even(n - 2),
    }
}
```

In terms of performance, this implementation has a better constant factor than the JavaScript version since it avoids multiple branches and function calls. However, for large inputs, recursion may result in stack overflow errors due to the deep call stack required. In such cases, an iterative approach or tail-recursive optimization would be more efficient.

To optimize for space usage, we can use a tail-recursive implementation that doesn't require a separate stack frame for each recursive call:

```rust
fn is_even_tailrec(n: i32, acc: bool) -> bool {
    match n {
        0 => acc,
        _ => is_even_tailrec(n - 2, !acc),
    }
}

fn is_even(n: i32) -> bool {
    is_even_tailrec(n, true)
}
```

